(18, 2, 8, '<h1>Coaching</h1>\n<h2>Spotting your career: a new way of coaching</h2>\n<p>In the first year coaching will be focussed on choosing your electives.</p>\n<p>In the second and third year we challenge you to explore what kind of career you want to strive for. What is needed for such a career? What do you want to develop during your student life?</p>\n<h2>First year</h2>\n<p>You have to submit your electives of the first year in the first quartile. Information on the electives will be provided in this study guide and in a special information session in week 4 of the first quartile. (Details on this session will be sent by email.) You will discuss your options and considerations with your mentor group. And on top of that, an e-counter will be provided where you can pose your questions or request a meeting with a teacher coach.</p>\n<p>You have to submit your elective program for year 2 and 3 in the fourth quartile. Again, information will be provided by several media. And when in doubt, ask for a meeting with one of our experienced coaches.</p>\n<h2>Choose your coach model in the second year</h2>\n<p>From the second year on, we offer a choice:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>an on-demand version of coaching, where you can ask your question at the e-counter, or ask for a one-to-one meeting with a coach</li>\n<li>a structured process of coaching, with group meetings every quartile, helping you to spot your career</li>\n<li>a flexible process of coaching where you have a say in how to spot your career, and how to spend the group budget.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Both for model 2 and 3 your commitment is required: prepare and actively attend the meetings. See manuals for more information.</p>\n<p>Your win is the opportunity to explore what kind of career suits you best. And that helps in choosing your master program, or in or perhaps in deciding not to proceed in one. Maybe you decide to even change your elective program in the bachelor. And you will be much more confident and convincing when pitching yourself for a panel of recruiters (which is one of the assignments in the final bachelor project ....). As an extra incentive you will get an exemption for most reflection assignments in the third year (embedded in the final project). This opportunity is only provided for students who have been active in model 2 or 3 for the whole period.</p>\n<p>You have to choose a model at the beginning of the second year. Enrollment through course code 2ICC2 (second-year students only).</p>\n<p>In model 2 and 3 you will be assigned a group and a coach.</p>\n<p>Over the year you can only switch to model 1.</p>\n<p>At the beginning of the third year you can choose to switch from model 2 or 3 to model 1, or from 2 to 3, or from 1 to 2.Enrollment through course code 2ICC3 (third-year students only).</p>\n<p>More information will be provided during the kick-off meetings in the first quartile.</p>\n \n \n<h2>Advisors & Tutors</h2>\n<p>Major P&T en SI (vanaf jaar 2), Bachelor TIW, Master HTI en IS:</p>\n<p>Ir. W.L.M. Kuijpers</p>\n<p>Pav. C13</p>\n<p>T: 040 247 46 50</p>\n<p>E: W.L.M.Kuijpers@tue.nl</p>\n\n<p>Major P&T en SI (eerstejaars):</p>\n<p>Mw. Mr. M. van de Ven</p>\n<p>Pav. A8a</p>\n<p>T: 040 247 50 61</p>\n<p>E: M.v.d.ven@tue.nl</p>\n\n<p>Major TBdk, Bachelor TBdk & TBG:</p>\n<p>Mw. ing. B. Osinga-Kuipers</p>\n<p>Pav. C14</p>\n<p>T: 040 247 28 75</p>\n<p>E: B.Osinga@tue.nl</p>\n\n<p>Premaster HTI, IS, IM en OML, Master IM en OML:</p>\n<p>Mw. ir. A.C.J. Kirkels-van Steen</p>\n<p>Pav. C15</p>\n<p>T: 040 247 24 73</p>\n<p>E: A.C.J.Kirkels@tue.nl</p>\n\n<p>Secretariaat Studieadviseurs IE&IS:<p>\n<p>Pav. C06</p>\n<p>T: 040 247 24 28</p>\n<p>E: Studieadviseurs.IEIS@tue.nl</p>\n\n\n', 'en', '2017-04-04 13:14:19', '2017-04-04 13:09:54'),
(19, 2, 9, '\n<h1>Regulations</h1>\n<p><strong>This is an universal page and is the same for every bachelor-program</strong></p>\n<p>The PER is the Program and Examination Regulations for a program and contains clear and sufficient information about the program, making it the basic document for both students and teachers.</p>\n<p>Subjects covered by the PER include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>the content of the program and the associated final examinations, the number and sequence of other examinations and the times when these can be taken</li>\n<li>the type of examination (oral, written or other types of examination)</li>\n<li> the period of validity of successfully completed examination components</li>\n<li> the right of inspection and evaluation</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Higher Education and Research Act (Wet op het hoger onderwijs en wetenschappelijk onderzoek) draws a distinction between program and examination regulations and examination committee rules and guidelines. Subjects regulated by the TU/e Examination Committee Rules and Guidelines (Examination Regulations) include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>compilation Examination Committee</li>\n<li>procedures Examination Committee</li>\n<li>tasks Examination Committee</li>\n<li>rules relating to quality assurance of testing and exams</li>\n<li>rules relating to measures taken in the event of fraud by examinees</li>\n<li>rules and guidelines relating to testing and exams</li>\n<li>compensation regulations</i>\n<li>graduation regulations</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Forms</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://static.studiegids.tue.nl/fileadmin/content/Faculteit_WenI/Bachelor_College/Reglementen/vrijstelling_Engels.pdf">Form Exemption</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://static.studiegids.tue.nl/fileadmin/content/Faculteit_WenI/Bachelor_College/Reglementen/vrijstelling_Engels_homologation.pdf">Request for Exemption pre-Master</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://static.studiegids.tue.nl/fileadmin/content/Faculteit_WenI/Bachelor_College/Reglementen/confidential.doc">Confidential Report Form</a></li>\n</u>\n \n\n', 'en', '2017-04-05 15:53:26', '2017-04-04 13:09:54'),
(20, 2, 10, '<h1>Subsequent masters</h1>\n<p>In this overview, we describe the admission criteria for enrollment in a number of relevant MSc-programs as we know them right now. Please visit the MSc-websites and/or contact the MSc-programs directly in case you have further questions.</p>\n<h2>Master Human-technology interaction</h2>\n<p>PT students have direct access, regardless of their specialisation. For more info <a href="/master/human-technology-interaction/overview">click here</a>.</p>\n<h2>Master Innovation Sciences</h2>\n<p>PT-students have to choose two electives (regardless of their specialisation).</p>\n<ol>\n<li>0SV10 Technology in society: Introduction Q2, timeslot C</li>\n<li>0SV30 Economics of Innovation: Introduction, Q1, timeslot E</li>\n</ol>\n<p>NB Students from other Majors also need to choose 0HV50 Research Methods 2, Q2, timeslot D.</p>\n<h2>Master Business Information Systems or Computer Science and Engineering</h2>\n<p>PT-ICT students are allowed in the BIS resp CSE Master if they choose two elective packages (Computer Science Essentials and Preparation Master BIS resp CSE). Only one course may be missing, which will be included in the elective space of the Master. More information: Michel Westenberg, director Graduate programs Computer Science).</p>\n<h2>Master Innovation Management</h2>\n<p>Students of the TU/e Bachelor College, not following the major Industrial Engineering and Management Science, will only be admitted if they have followed the elective package Innovation Management. We also recommend to follow the USE-package New Product Development and Marketing. Depending of the direction of your Major you have to follow some courses about business economics and research methods in the elective part of your Master''s program. The Admission Board decides which courses you have to follow. If you want more information about admission, please see <a href="https://studiegids.tue.nl/">website</a> or send an e-mail.</p>\n<h2>Master Operations Management & Logistics</h2>\n<p>Students of the TU/e Bachelor College, not following the Major Industrial Engineering and Management Science, will only be admitted if they have followed the elective package "Preparation Master OML for non-IE". The elective package consists of 3 courses out of 5, the other 2 can be part of the Master. Please note that the elective package does not imply that you are automatically admitted in the Master program. Each student should individually contact the FTC (facultaire toelatingscommissie).</p>\n<h2>Master Construction Management & Engineering</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>In principe is het voor alle PT en SI studenten mogelijk om in te stromen in CME; affiniteit met bouw/CME is natuurlijk wel wenselijk. Dit is eigen verantwoordelijkheid van de student.</li>\n<li>Voor de studenten die de bouwrichting doen (PT-Living and SI-Sustainable Living) is CME een aanbevolen doorstroomroute. Zij hebben in elk geval vier bouwkunde-vakken in hun Major gedaan</li>\n<li>Studenten die zich willen orienteren op en verder verdiepen in het vakgebied van CME wordt aangeraden het coherent keuzepakket ''Tussen droom en daad staan regels en feiten'' (nu: Urban Systems and Real Estate) te volgen. Het geheel of gedeeltelijk volgen van het coherent keuzepakket is niet verplicht, en eigen verantwoordelijkheid van de student. Een vak (7U9X0 Onderzoek en Statistiek) hoeft door de PT en SI studenten niet te worden gevolgd</li>\n<li>Studenten die vragen hebben over de inhoud van de Master of twijfelen over de inhoud van hun keuzepakket in de Bachelor kunnen contact opnemen met Wim Schaefer</li>\n</ul>\n\n', 'en', '2017-04-05 15:54:52', '2017-04-04 13:09:54'),
(21, 3, 12, 'Curriculum', 'en', '2017-04-04 14:37:11', '2017-04-04 14:37:11'),
(22, 3, 13, '<h1>Binding Study Recommendation</h1>\n<p><strong>This is an universal page and is the same for every pre-Master</p></strong>\n<p>Annex 3: Regulations for the pre-master''s programs for HBO and University bachelor graduates for transition to the subsequent Master''s programs according to Graduate School\nArticle 1 sub 3 - Premaster program for HBO and University bachelor graduates</p>\n<p>The student must complete the pre-master program within 12 months of the starting date. If the student does not meet the requirements as stated in the preceding sentence, the student will not be allowed to continue the pre-master program, nor shall he/she be admitted to the same or another pre-master program that belongs to the same Bachelor''s program for a period of three years. In special cases the Examinations Committee may at the request of the student deviate from this.\nFor more information, please read the PER (Program and Exam Regulations) Annex 2.</p>\n\n', 'en', '2017-04-05 15:55:22', '2017-04-04 14:37:11'),
(23, 3, 14, '<h1>Bachelor before Master</h1>\n<p><strong>This is an universal page and is the same for every pre-Master</strong></p>					\n<p>Starting September 2012, TU/e introduced the Bachelor-before-master rule (harde knip), which means that a student needs a bachelor diploma in order to be allowed to start a Master''s program. Although HBO-graduates have completed a bachelor program, TU/e considers them bachelor students until they have completed the pre-master program.</p>\n\n', 'en', '2017-04-05 15:55:39', '2017-04-04 14:37:11'),
(24, 3, 15, '<h1>15 credits regulation</h1>\n<p><strong>This is an universal page and is the same for every pre-Master</strong></p>\n<p>If a student cannot complete the pre-Master''s program within six months and therefore has a demonstrable disadvantage with completing it, but has a minimum of 15 ECTs, the student can request to expand the program with at most 15 ECTs in Master''s study components. The credits obtained for Master''s study components during the pre-Master''s program will be recorded on the student''s Master''s transcrept as exemptions.</p>\n<p>This is in accordance with OER MSc Graduate School 016 Annex 2 to article 3.2, paragraph 2, of the Education and Examination Regulations 2016 for the Master''s Degree Programs and  the Graduate School\nArticle 2-4</p>\n\n', 'en', '2017-04-05 15:31:44', '2017-04-04 14:37:11'),
(25, 3, 16, '<h1>Regulations</h1>\n<p><strong>This is an universal page and is the same for every pre-Master</p></strong>\n<p>Apart from the PER also consider the 15 credits regulation.</p>\n<h2>Program and Examination Regulations (PER)</h2>\n<p>The PER is the Program and Examination Regulations for a program and contains clear and sufficient information about the program, making it the basic document for both students and teachers.</p>\n<p>Subjects covered by the PER include:</p>\n<ul><li>the content of the program and the associated final examinations, the number and sequence of other examinations and the times when these can be taken</li>\n<li>the type of examination (oral, written or other types of examination)</li>\n<li>the period of validity of successfully completed examination components</li>\n<li>the right of inspection and evaluation</li></ul>\n<p>The Higher Education and Research Act (Wet op het hoger onderwijs en wetenschappelijk onderzoek) draws a distinction between program and examination regulations and examination committee rules and guidelines. Subjects regulated by the TU/e Examination Committee Rules and Guidelines (Examination Regulations) include:</p>\n<ul><li>compilation Examination Committee</li>\n<li>procedures Examination Committee</li>\n<li>tasks Examination Committee</li>\n<li>rules relating to quality assurance of testing and exams</li>\n<li>rules relating to measures taken in the event of fraud by examinees</li>\n<li>rules and guidelines relating to testing and exams</li>\n<li>compensation regulations</li>\n<li>graduation regulations</li></ul>\n<h2>Forms</h2>\n<ul><li><a href="https://static.studiegids.tue.nl/fileadmin/content/Faculteit_WenI/Bachelor_College/Reglementen/vrijstelling_Engels.pdf">Form exemption</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://static.studiegids.tue.nl/fileadmin/content/Faculteit_WenI/Bachelor_College/Reglementen/vrijstelling_Engels_homologation.pdf">Request for exemption homologation</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://static.st